Verse seven, your wrath weighs heavily on me.

19:07.646 --> 19:09.288
You have overwhelmed me with all your waves.

19:09.368 --> 19:11.431
Verse eight, you have distanced my friends.

19:11.671 --> 19:13.414
You have made me repulsive to them.

19:13.434 --> 19:19.782
This is when the theological word police, they're supposed to belay in, smash to the windows and say, hey, hey, we don't talk like that.

19:21.744 --> 19:23.707
It gets real, but it doesn't get that real.

19:24.608 --> 19:27.772
We don't say this kind of stuff.

19:27.792 --> 19:29.074
Look, God doesn't run in.

19:29.634 --> 19:35.430
and make sure all your statements in prayer are theologically tidy and properly nuanced when you're desperate.

19:37.115 --> 19:38.018
That's such good news.

19:38.720 --> 19:41.247
God is not put off by your desperation.

19:42.852 --> 19:45.138
He wants us to run to him.

19:47.330 --> 19:48.712
Now look, just back up for a second.

19:48.732 --> 20:00.705
So this song doesn't actually give us enough information to assess, to evaluate whether he's actually experiencing the sweeping torments of the wrath of God on his soul, whether God is really out to get him.

20:00.986 --> 20:10.957
This song doesn't give us enough information to find out if God is actually intentionally, sovereignly distancing his friends, shoving his friends away so that he's totally isolated.

20:11.217 --> 20:13.500
But look, that's not the point of the passage.

20:13.520 --> 20:15.442
He's not writing a seminary thesis.

20:16.162 --> 20:17.423
He's telling God how he feels.

20:19.185 --> 20:21.688
And this is how it honestly feels at Landfall.

20:22.749 --> 20:23.610
This is what it feels like.

20:25.593 --> 20:38.127
Let me just say, on balance, Psalm 88 is not a license to spew venom into heaven, to let loose with accusations, bitter accusations against God.

20:38.147 --> 20:39.188
That is not what's happening here.

20:39.488 --> 20:44.754
What we see happening in Psalm 88 is this is a man wrestling with the tension between what he knows and what he feels.

20:46.274 --> 20:52.263
What he knows about God, he front loads in the first five words, and there's no clearer theology in the entire Psalm than the first five words.

20:52.643 --> 20:56.069
Lord, God of my salvation doesn't get any better.

20:56.269 --> 20:57.451
That's the absolute truth.

20:57.511 --> 20:58.332
That is his name.

20:58.652 --> 20:59.494
That is what he does.

20:59.794 --> 21:02.799
He is a God of salvation, not just salvation abstractly.

21:02.979 --> 21:05.182
You're the God of my salvation.

21:06.384 --> 21:08.367
So he knows and he puts that right up front.

21:08.387 --> 21:12.313
The problem is it's not leveraging any difference in his own personal life and experience.

21:12.333 --> 21:13.735
His feelings aren't buying it.

21:15.037 --> 21:15.858
It's truth.

21:16.226 --> 21:18.008
But his feelings aren't buying it.

21:18.128 --> 21:19.770
I know you're the God of my salvation.

21:19.810 --> 21:20.691
That's why I said it.

21:22.273 --> 21:27.058
But my experience is telling me you're not saving anything or anyone today.

21:28.620 --> 21:30.802
You're not doing any saving today.

21:33.005 --> 21:41.074
It's possible to have faith, genuine faith, and feel cut off from the favor of God.

21:42.978 --> 21:47.243
It is possible to have genuine faith and feel cut off from the blessing of God.

21:47.724 --> 21:52.209
Not only do we have that all over the Psalms, it's all over church history.

21:52.249 --> 21:58.216
Some of the greatest leaders that God has raised up in the last 2000 years of church history were benighted leaders.

21:59.678 --> 22:09.650
Walk through great darkness of soul, the great hymn writer, William Cooper, author of there as a fountain filled with blood, attempted suicide multiple times.

22:11.874 --> 22:18.903
That's why he was riding back and forth with his best friend, John Newton, who was attending to his soul for years and years and years.

22:19.124 --> 22:22.468
Luther, Bunyan, Brainerd, Spurgeon.

22:22.488 --> 22:29.958
It's practically a whose list of the last 2,000 years all felt deep torment of soul from time to time.

22:30.479 --> 22:32.301
Mental anguish from time to time Spurgeon.

22:33.323 --> 22:38.810
Nine years into his marriage with Susanna, his wife Susanna, and she became virtually homebound.

22:40.392 --> 22:41.874
They couldn't figure out what was wrong with her.

22:42.242 --> 22:49.412
And so for the next 27 years, she almost attended no services and never heard her husband preach, the great Prince of Preachers.

22:50.673 --> 22:51.415
And she's homebound.

22:52.937 --> 22:59.566
Spurgeon himself, greatly afflicted with all kinds of trials, physical suffering, physical symptoms.

22:59.986 --> 23:04.993
The last two decades of his ministry, one-third of the Sundays, he was out sick.

23:06.495 --> 23:11.602
One-third of 22 years of Sundays, he was out sick or out recovering.

23:13.250 --> 23:23.943
And he writes of one particular Sunday when he was preaching, and he was preaching Psalm 22 when a great lament Psalms, the famous one, my God, my God, why have you forsaken me?

23:23.983 --> 23:25.665
This is what Spurgeon wrote about it.

23:27.247 --> 23:33.134
Though I did not say so, yet I preached my own experience.

23:33.154 --> 23:39.442
I heard my own chains clank while I tried to preach to my fellow prisoners in the dark.

23:40.482 --> 23:51.523
And a man came up to him after he preached that sermon and feeling God forsaken and a man said, I've never heard a preacher so fully describe my life as that sermon.

23:52.325 --> 24:03.186
And Spurgeon was thinking, it's because I preach from my own life, from my own experience, chains clanking while he preached to prisoners in the dark.

24:05.666 --> 24:10.493
This psalmist is desperate and he can't see any reason why it's time to hide that.

24:11.134 --> 24:13.097
He brings it to the presence of God.

24:13.117 --> 24:17.805
And then the text really changes direction from desperation to point number two argument.

24:20.068 --> 24:21.550
Argument, do you work wonders?

24:21.590 --> 24:23.934
He asks, do you work wonders for the dead?

24:25.777 --> 24:30.184
Now these are not questions in one sense, they're rhetorical arguments.

24:31.766 --> 24:34.450
So he's stockpiling questions

24:34.722 --> 24:38.628
that to his way of thinking, to the Old Testament way of thinking, demand the answer no.

24:39.029 --> 24:39.490
You notice that.

24:39.510 --> 24:43.276
When you read those questions, all of them are tilted toward no.

24:43.336 --> 24:46.701
The answer is of course no to each one of these questions.

24:46.721 --> 24:50.908
And if the answer is no, then that suggests a call to action.

24:51.389 --> 24:59.442
God, step forward, save, glorify yourself, demonstrate your faithfulness here, now.

25:00.706 --> 25:09.817
Now, just back up for a second, because when it comes to what happens after death, when it comes to the doctrine of resurrection, the Old Testament saints were largely in the dark.

25:11.299 --> 25:15.284
It's not like that had a ton of things to understand about this back there in the Old Testament.

25:15.304 --> 25:20.870
The blessed hope, if you will, for most Old Testament patriarchs wasn't to die and go to heaven.

25:21.732 --> 25:23.794
It was to live to see your children's children.

25:25.634 --> 25:30.938
That's what their great desire was to live out their days in the Promised Land.

25:30.979 --> 25:32.646
And that didn't mean that one.

25:32.747 --> 25:34.354
It meant the one they were standing on.

25:35.234 --> 25:38.718
Or if they were in exile, it meant the one that they wanted to go back to, their homeland.

25:38.738 --> 25:39.439
They were outside.

25:39.459 --> 25:44.105
They wanted to go back to their homeland and raise their families and olive orchards and fig trees.

25:44.385 --> 25:51.073
And the blessing of God and the land of the living, the land of the living is such a huge phrase for the aspiration of the psalmist throughout the psalmist.

25:51.093 --> 25:54.878
And the land of the living show your favor and your blessing.

25:54.898 --> 26:01.586
So there are hints of resurrection tucked back there in the Old Testament in Psalm 16.

26:01.858 --> 26:09.627
two verses in Isaiah, one verse in Hosea, a few other places, hints of resurrection, hints of life after death.

26:10.267 --> 26:13.691
But we can't make Old Testament saints pass New Testament exams.

26:15.413 --> 26:24.523
As if they had read 1 Corinthians 15 with all of its exalting doctrine of the physical resurrection of Jesus and being a first fruits for everybody who believes.

26:25.244 --> 26:30.770
But being an inspired biblical writer didn't mean that they got this matrix plug into the back of their head.

26:31.650 --> 26:35.215
And it just downloaded all this future information into their heads.

26:35.275 --> 26:40.283
And suddenly they got future names and places and Jesus Christ and where He's going to be.

26:40.323 --> 26:41.965
And all of that just presents itself.

26:41.985 --> 26:43.487
And they come up and their eyes open.

26:43.507 --> 26:44.569
They say, the tomb is empty.

26:44.589 --> 26:45.590
And everybody says, what tomb?

26:45.610 --> 26:47.593
What are you talking about?

26:47.613 --> 26:49.636
No, they didn't have some secret download.

26:49.676 --> 26:52.901
They didn't come out of that moment quoting the Apostle Paul.

26:52.981 --> 26:57.107
Jesus Christ has brought life and immortality to light through the gospel.

26:57.668 --> 26:58.028
Awesome.

26:58.349 --> 26:59.250
They didn't notice that.

27:00.450 --> 27:02.952
progressive revelation is really progressive revelation.

27:03.032 --> 27:06.976
God is stepping out of hiding more and more throughout the Old Testament.

27:08.297 --> 27:09.438
It shouldn't surprise us.

27:10.159 --> 27:11.040
It shouldn't even surprise us.

27:11.080 --> 27:17.306
In the pages of the New Testament, for example, in Mark chapter nine, Jesus is coming down after the Mount of Transfiguration event.

27:17.926 --> 27:19.368
He's coming down with Peter, James, and John.

27:19.408 --> 27:21.430
This is the inner circle of the inner circle.

27:22.370 --> 27:24.472
And they've already spent two and a half years with Jesus.

27:25.493 --> 27:26.775
And they're coming down from the mountain.

27:26.855 --> 27:30.418
And Jesus says, don't tell anybody what you just saw, quote,

27:30.562 --> 27:33.227
until the Son of Man has risen from the dead.

27:33.888 --> 27:40.521
And the very next verse reads this way, Mark 9, 10, they kept this word to themselves, questioning what rising from the dead meant.

27:42.946 --> 27:45.470
What on earth is he talking about rising from the dead?

27:48.857 --> 27:51.602
So don't make Old Testament saints pass

27:51.746 --> 27:55.890
New Testament exams and understand New Testament clear realities.

27:55.930 --> 28:10.003
But having said that, even though there are some things in which the New Testament sheds more light on it later on, still, as it is right here in this text, there is huge profound truth tucked into these questions.

28:10.084 --> 28:11.245
And the truth is this.

28:12.206 --> 28:18.592
God gets unique glory and praise when he rescues his people in this life in the side of the nations.

28:19.292 --> 28:21.074
And that's a huge truth.

28:21.154 --> 28:23.196
shot through the entire Old Testament.

28:23.216 --> 28:27.340
You think about, so for example, when he says, will your wonders be known in the darkness?

28:29.262 --> 28:31.244
Will departed spirits rise up to praise you?

28:31.564 --> 28:34.206
Will your miracles be praised by the dead?

28:34.246 --> 28:37.990
You think about the great rescuing act of the entire Old Testament, the Exodus.

28:38.510 --> 28:41.794
Ask the question, what happens to the Old Testament if the Exodus never happens?

28:43.395 --> 28:46.178
What happens if the people die in chains in Egypt?

28:46.558 --> 28:50.642
They never come out, they never cross the Red Sea, they die in chains.

28:51.746 --> 28:52.327
What happens?

28:52.827 --> 28:54.970
The whole Old Testament changes.

28:55.170 --> 28:55.871
That's what happens.

28:57.072 --> 29:06.182
That massive outburst of praise for God, for Yahweh, on the distant shore of the Red Sea after God caused the waters to part.

29:06.422 --> 29:08.605
That worship never happens.

29:09.085 --> 29:11.668
Miriam never plays her famous tambourine.

29:11.708 --> 29:13.750
The song of Moses never gets written.

29:13.991 --> 29:15.112
Everything changes.

29:16.313 --> 29:20.658
There is a glory God receives when he saves us from death.

29:21.250 --> 29:33.142
Not just through death, from death, when he takes away ashes and gives garments of praise, instead, when he rescues marriages here, and when he writes new stories, God gets glory from that.

29:34.763 --> 29:47.996
When he acts in powerful ways here and now, and in that way, the psalmist, he might lack a full understanding of the doctrine of resurrection, but he's onto something huge, and he's pressing that point home with these questions.

29:48.577 --> 29:49.938
Are you gonna get the glory?

29:51.170 --> 29:55.516
for being faithful if I die here while heaven is silent.

29:55.916 --> 29:56.878
Are you going to get that glory?

29:58.280 --> 30:00.643
It brings us to the third refrain.

30:00.723 --> 30:05.049
So we move from desperation to argument to isolation.

30:07.753 --> 30:08.834
Why do you hide?

30:09.255 --> 30:11.337
He says, your face for me.

30:14.161 --> 30:16.444
And this is the deepest pain a believer can experience.

30:16.485 --> 30:20.530
The pain of feeling God is absent.

30:20.834 --> 30:28.165
silence of God, the silence of heaven, feeling like when you pray you're talking to the walls.

30:28.746 --> 30:36.137
Look, it's impossible to know exactly what kind of experience he's facing back there in history.

30:36.317 --> 30:37.699
Is this mental anguish?

30:38.541 --> 30:40.744
Is this spiritual attack?

30:40.764 --> 30:42.226
Is this physical

30:42.338 --> 30:53.489
suffering, primarily physical suffering, and now he's terminal, and he's isolated from his friends because he has something that they'll catch if they come into the rooms, and maybe that's why he's distanced from all of his loved ones, and his friends is a physical thing.

30:53.769 --> 31:00.136
Or is it all those things combined together, just this whole perfect storm in his life?

31:02.018 --> 31:08.244
Whatever it might be specifically, the final straw, the thing that makes this absolutely unlivable, is he's alone.

31:09.845 --> 31:10.546
He's dying?

31:11.586 --> 31:15.812
Heaven is painfully silent and he's alone.

31:19.837 --> 31:25.344
For it's possible to have faith and feel burdened beyond our strength.

31:26.907 --> 31:28.088
Some of you need to hear this.

31:29.230 --> 31:33.575
It's possible to have faith, genuine faith, and feel burdened beyond your strength.

31:33.656 --> 31:38.482
It's possible to have faith and feel that God is hiding from you.

31:39.234 --> 31:47.145
It's possible to have faith and wrestle with very hard questions about God is possible to have faith and yet every day with Jesus not be sweeter than the one before.

31:47.166 --> 31:48.808
That's possible.

31:48.848 --> 31:56.139
It's possible to know God as God of my salvation and yet feel convinced there won't be any saving today.

31:56.199 --> 31:57.040
That's possible.

31:59.684 --> 32:04.711
In a word, it's possible to have a right knowledge of God and yet that knowledge not yield.

32:05.853 --> 32:06.834
It's full.

32:07.202 --> 32:13.328
soul-stabilizing effect in your experience, in every moment of your life.

32:13.408 --> 32:15.049
That is possible.

32:16.371 --> 32:17.492
So where is faith?

32:17.512 --> 32:23.277
I mean, some of you might read the darkness of Psalm 88 and say, if this is faith, what's not faith?

32:25.139 --> 32:26.200
Look how darkness is.

32:26.220 --> 32:28.662
Look how hopeless and despairing this is.

32:29.143 --> 32:32.766
If that's not unbelief, I don't know what unbelief is.

32:33.347 --> 32:36.690
Where is faith in the most misery-laden Psalm in the entire Bible?

32:37.378 --> 32:45.949
Don't forget this little whispered chorus that carries you through from moment to moment to moment, verse nine, one in nine and 13.

32:45.969 --> 32:47.290
I cry out.

32:48.512 --> 32:49.433
I cry out.

32:50.514 --> 32:51.255
I call out.

32:52.817 --> 32:57.022
What keeps this man talking to God when his experience tells him nobody's listening?

32:59.265 --> 33:00.707
What keeps him asking for help?

33:00.987 --> 33:02.649
What keeps him desiring?

33:02.749 --> 33:06.514
The motive behind these questions makes it clear.

33:06.658 --> 33:07.980
God's glory.

33:08.020 --> 33:10.604
He wants God to get praise for being faithful.

33:10.624 --> 33:12.687
It is a God-centered motivation.

33:12.748 --> 33:16.353
What makes him want to declare God's praise when his prayers keep going unanswered?

33:16.974 --> 33:24.586
Look, what we see in this psalm is a man calling out, crying out, crying out to God in the midst of total devastation.

33:24.666 --> 33:25.828
And the Bible has a word for that.

33:26.709 --> 33:27.731
It's called faith.

33:29.674 --> 33:34.802
Real faith, not faith that's hinged on blessings, faith that trust in God, period.

33:35.970 --> 33:37.091
Because God is faithful.

33:37.552 --> 33:37.912
Period.

33:37.993 --> 33:38.914
God is true.

33:39.675 --> 33:40.135
Period.

33:40.776 --> 33:44.641
Faith that clings to Him with every fiber of our being.

33:44.962 --> 33:47.044
And look, Psalm 88 is in the end of the story.

33:49.467 --> 33:50.048
Point number four.

33:51.730 --> 33:52.351
Restoration.

33:54.394 --> 33:57.097
How the story ends and how we help each other.

33:59.921 --> 34:03.986
So we have 150 Psalms here in the book of Psalms.

34:04.130 --> 34:13.923
150 are actually divided up more than, and they still are in our English Bibles now, divided up into five books, five mini collections of Psalms.

34:13.943 --> 34:31.826
Matter of fact, if you just wanna flip the page and look at Psalm 90, right in your Bible, just flip the page, look at Psalm 90 and you see the word book four, because back then they had these divided up into five books and they didn't divide them up in this chronological way.

34:32.674 --> 34:38.563
It's not like the early Psalms written by Moses are all first and then the ones by David and others are later on.

34:39.024 --> 34:45.093
Psalm 90 is a Psalm of Moses who lived five, 600 years before the guy who's writing this Psalm.

34:45.113 --> 34:49.840
So they're not arranged chronologically, they're arranged to tell a story.

34:51.122 --> 35:01.618
They've been put in this order to tell the story of the pilgrimage into which God has brought his people and God is taking his people from suffering to glory.

35:02.050 --> 35:11.446
That's what the vast sweeping, this sort of undercurrent underneath the entire Psalter is this story of God taking his people from suffering to glory.

35:11.466 --> 35:13.089
And he's with them every step of the way.

35:13.129 --> 35:13.830
So here we are.

35:14.111 --> 35:23.186
We're at the end, as you see in Psalm 90, if that's book four begins, we're at the end of book three and book four changes tonally.

35:23.778 --> 35:31.568
The tone changes, the 90s are high with praise, high with exaltation, high with trust in a sovereign and awesome God.

35:31.848 --> 35:38.337
And the tone that's changing here beginning in book four and book five, that's even born out statistically.

35:38.417 --> 35:42.562
So if you go back, you can check this out and just read through the Psalms and look for this.

35:42.622 --> 35:44.665
But book one to book three.

35:44.725 --> 35:46.607
So that's Psalms one through Psalm 89.

35:48.029 --> 35:51.954
The Psalms of lament, like this one, cries of anguish.

35:52.226 --> 35:56.114
outnumber hymns of praise 2 to 1, a little more than 2 to 1.

35:56.956 --> 36:02.468
In book 4 and 5, from Psalm 90 to Psalm 150, those proportions are reversed.

36:03.289 --> 36:07.759
And now the hymns of praise outnumber the laments 2 to 1, plus some.

36:08.580 --> 36:09.362
And so we

36:10.210 --> 36:30.226
get this picture of what's happening here, this big sweeping story of God and his people comes full circle where we move, as we read through the book of Psalms, we move from what began in anguish ends in Psalm 150 with trumpets and tambourines and symbols and let everything that has breath praise the Lord.

36:30.927 --> 36:34.834
Creatures, hosts, angels, it's the triumph

36:35.810 --> 36:42.279
It's the glory that comes after the suffering that really in a way the whole story of the Psalms could be summarized with a Psalm.

36:43.200 --> 36:49.369
Many are the afflictions of the righteous, but at the end of the day, the Lord delivers them out of them all.

36:49.389 --> 36:59.122
That's the story of the Psalter and the whole story of the Psalter pivots in real history on Jesus Christ.

37:00.930 --> 37:05.468
Jesus Christ steps into the world and he takes up the anguish of Psalm 88.

37:05.608 --> 37:08.178
He steps into the shoes of

37:08.450 --> 37:13.978
Psalm 88, he was the only truly God forsaken person who ever lived.

37:13.998 --> 37:19.085
And he hung there on the cross and he said, my God, why have you forsaken me?

37:19.105 --> 37:22.090
And he wasn't crossing his fingers behind his back or winking.

37:22.210 --> 37:25.815
It was a real forsakenness, not a fake one, not a pretended one.

37:26.236 --> 37:27.598
He was really forsaken.

37:27.618 --> 37:30.001
The father really turned his back on the sun.

37:30.322 --> 37:33.426
He really felt the sweeping wrath of God

37:33.506 --> 37:36.911
pour over him under his billows of his wrath.

37:36.991 --> 37:40.917
And we know why because we have a New Testament.

37:40.937 --> 37:45.244
He was forsaken so that you would never have to be forsaken.

37:45.264 --> 37:49.771
He was forsaken so that if you trust in Jesus Christ, you will never be forsaken.

37:50.011 --> 37:54.618
He was friendless at the cross so that we could know the friendship of God.

37:55.479 --> 37:56.381
That's the gospel.

37:57.162 --> 37:58.784
It all hinges on Jesus.

37:59.045 --> 38:02.610
All hope in scripture comes through, is mediated

38:02.722 --> 38:03.343
through Jesus.

38:03.423 --> 38:07.727
But look, even though we know that, even though that's precious truth, we still need Psalm 88.

38:09.589 --> 38:15.475
We still need Psalm 88 because the world hasn't become any more heaven-like in the 3,000 years since this Psalm was written.

38:16.856 --> 38:21.721
